I"ñ<p>Given that <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/exosomatic-memories-are-cues">exosomatic memories are often cues</a>, and that <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/multi-modal-mappings-generate-multi-modal-receptive-fields">machine learning models are fluent in multimedia content</a>, and that <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/recent-memories-are-malleable">memories are malleable</a>, then malicious memory cues could be engineered to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memory-is-perception-of-structural-artifacts">distort the past</a>. This is likely due to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/epistemic-action-generalizes-cognitive-outsourcing">our regular outsourcing of thinking to the world</a>.</p>
